ic spaces, Navarātri is one of the most important and ubiquitous festivals in South Asia and wherever South Asians have settled. These festivals share many elements, including the goddess, royal power, the killing of demons, and the worship of young girls and married women, but their interpretation and performance vary widely. This interdisciplinary collection of essays investigates Navarātri in its many manifestations and across historical periods, including celebrations in West Bengal, Odisha, Karnataka, Maharashtra, Tamil Nadu, Uttar Pradesh, and Nepal. Collectively, the essays consider the role of the festival's contextual specificity and continental ubiquity as a central component for understanding South Asian religious life, as well as how it shapes and is shaped by political patronage, economic development, and social status.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDurgā-pūjā (Hindu festival)zSouth Asia. 0aFasts and feastsxHinduism. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Cultural Anthropology. 4aAnthropology and Archaeology : Ethnography. 4aAsian Studies : India and South Asian Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Hindu Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aBalkaran, Raj, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEinarsen, Silje Lyngar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHÜSken, Ute, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuchesi, Brigitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLunde Ilkama, Ina Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNarayanan, Vasudha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodrigues, Hillary Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato